00:01:47.650 --> 00:01:49.630
So let's dive right in.

00:01:49.630 --> 00:01:53.610
One thing that people may
not know about "Allegiance"

00:01:53.610 --> 00:01:58.880
is that it's inspired by your
very childhood and your years

00:01:58.880 --> 00:02:02.320
while imprisoned during the
Japanese American internment,

00:02:02.320 --> 00:02:05.610
and that you yourself
were an internee.

00:02:05.610 --> 00:02:07.430
GEORGE TAKEI: Yes,
that is correct.

00:02:07.430 --> 00:02:08.979
JULIE JAMES: It's unbelievable.

00:02:08.979 --> 00:02:12.750
So tell us a little
bit more about that.

00:02:12.750 --> 00:02:18.520
GEORGE TAKEI: Well, Japan bombed
Pearl Harbor, as you know,

00:02:18.520 --> 00:02:23.600
on December 7, 1941 and that
plunged the whole world it

00:02:23.600 --> 00:02:27.440
into another world war.

00:02:27.440 --> 00:02:31.850
For Japanese Americans, American
citizens of Japanese ancestry,

00:02:31.850 --> 00:02:34.890
it was a catastrophic
experience.

00:02:34.890 --> 00:02:38.270
Because overnight,
we were looked

00:02:38.270 --> 00:02:46.630
at with suspicion and fear
and outright hatred simply

00:02:46.630 --> 00:02:49.060
because we happened to
look like the people that

00:02:49.060 --> 00:02:50.820
bombed Pearl Harbor.

00:02:50.820 --> 00:02:57.900
And the hysteria grew and grew
until on February 19, 1942,

00:02:57.900 --> 00:02:59.550
the President of
the United States,

00:02:59.550 --> 00:03:03.540
Franklin Delano Roosevelt,
ordered all Japanese Americans

00:03:03.540 --> 00:03:06.930
on the West Coast,
approximately 120,000

00:03:06.930 --> 00:03:12.110
of us, to be summarily
rounded up, with no charges,

00:03:12.110 --> 00:03:17.420
with no trial, with no due
process, the central pillar

00:03:17.420 --> 00:03:20.430
of our justice
system, and ordered

00:03:20.430 --> 00:03:25.890
them to be incarcerated in
10 barbed wire prison camps,

00:03:25.890 --> 00:03:29.110
in some of the most god
awful places in this country.

00:03:29.110 --> 00:03:32.080
The blistering hot
desert of Arizona,

00:03:32.080 --> 00:03:37.320
the sultry swamps of Arkansas,
southeastern Arkansas,

00:03:37.320 --> 00:03:42.380
the cold windswept high plains
of Wyoming, Idaho, Utah,

00:03:42.380 --> 00:03:47.840
Colorado, and two of the most
desolate places in California.

00:03:47.840 --> 00:03:52.890
On April 20, I celebrated my
fifth birthday and my parents

00:03:52.890 --> 00:03:55.290
tell me that they gave
me a birthday party,

00:03:55.290 --> 00:03:57.910
but I don't remember that.

00:03:57.910 --> 00:04:03.300
Because a few weeks after that
my parents got me, my brother,

00:04:03.300 --> 00:04:10.380
a year younger, and my baby
sister, not yet a year old,

00:04:10.380 --> 00:04:14.860
they got us up very early,
and they hurriedly dressed us.

00:04:14.860 --> 00:04:19.630
And my brother and I were in
the living room looking out

00:04:19.630 --> 00:04:23.790
the front window, and we
saw two soldiers marching up

00:04:23.790 --> 00:04:25.350
our driveway.

00:04:25.350 --> 00:04:28.290
They carried rifles
with bayonets

00:04:28.290 --> 00:04:31.000
shining on top of them.

00:04:31.000 --> 00:04:35.540
They stomped up the front porch
and banged on the front door.

00:04:35.540 --> 00:04:39.860
My father answered it and
literally at gunpoint,

00:04:39.860 --> 00:04:42.810
we were ordered out of our home.

00:04:42.810 --> 00:04:45.910
My father gave my brother and
me little pieces of luggage

00:04:45.910 --> 00:04:49.050
to carry, and we went
out on the driveway

00:04:49.050 --> 00:04:52.160
and waited for our
mother to come out.

00:04:52.160 --> 00:04:54.670
She took some time.

00:04:54.670 --> 00:04:58.810
And when she finally
emerged she had our baby

00:04:58.810 --> 00:05:02.160
sister in one arm
and a huge duffel bag

00:05:02.160 --> 00:05:09.230
in the other and tears were
streaming down both her cheeks.

00:05:09.230 --> 00:05:12.200
I may have been five years
old, but I will never

00:05:12.200 --> 00:05:15.750
forget that terrifying morning.

00:05:15.750 --> 00:05:19.860
We were taken from our
home on a truck where

00:05:19.860 --> 00:05:23.370
there were other Japanese
American families gathered

00:05:23.370 --> 00:05:27.560
to Santa Anita racetrack,
a nearby racetrack,

00:05:27.560 --> 00:05:32.160
and driven to the stable
area where we were unloaded.

00:05:32.160 --> 00:05:37.170
And we were herded over
to the stable area.

00:05:37.170 --> 00:05:42.130
And we were told by the soldiers
that this one horse stall would

00:05:42.130 --> 00:05:45.020
be where we would
stay temporarily

00:05:45.020 --> 00:05:47.840
while the camps are being built.

00:05:47.840 --> 00:05:52.250
All five of us, three
children and our parents,

00:05:52.250 --> 00:05:57.740
moved from a two bedroom home
on Garnet Street in Los Angeles

00:05:57.740 --> 00:06:01.450
to this smelly horse stall.

00:06:01.450 --> 00:06:06.710
For my parents, it was a
degrading, humiliating, painful

00:06:06.710 --> 00:06:10.460
experience, but for
five-year-old me

00:06:10.460 --> 00:06:12.390
I thought it was
kind of fun that we

00:06:12.390 --> 00:06:15.510
get to sleep where
the horseys sleep.

00:06:15.510 --> 00:06:19.280
If you breathe deeply,
you can smell them.

00:06:19.280 --> 00:06:21.520
So we were there
for a few months

00:06:21.520 --> 00:06:26.360
and then the construction
of the camps was completed,

00:06:26.360 --> 00:06:29.960
and we were put on trains
with armed soldiers

00:06:29.960 --> 00:06:36.030
at both ends of each car,
as if we were criminals.

00:06:36.030 --> 00:06:40.060
And we were transported 2/3
of the way across the country

00:06:40.060 --> 00:06:44.130
to the swamps of
southeastern Arkansas.

00:06:44.130 --> 00:06:48.790
I still remember the barbed
wire fences that confined me.

00:06:48.790 --> 00:06:53.760
The tall sentry towers with
the machine guns pointed at us.

00:06:53.760 --> 00:06:55.850
I remember the searchlight
that followed me

00:06:55.850 --> 00:06:59.810
when I made the night
runs to the latrine.

00:06:59.810 --> 00:07:04.260
But young children are
amazingly adaptable.

00:07:04.260 --> 00:07:08.520
What would be grotesquely
abnormal in normal times

00:07:08.520 --> 00:07:13.630
became my normality behind
those barbed wire fences.

00:07:13.630 --> 00:07:16.070
It became normal for me
to the line up three times

00:07:16.070 --> 00:07:20.720
a day to eat lousy food
in a noisy mess hall.

00:07:20.720 --> 00:07:23.740
It became routine for me
to go to a mass shower

00:07:23.740 --> 00:07:25.980
with my father.

00:07:25.980 --> 00:07:29.530
And it became normal for me
to go to school in a black tar

00:07:29.530 --> 00:07:31.930
paper barrack and
begin the school

00:07:31.930 --> 00:07:36.180
day with the Pledge of
Allegiance to the flag.

00:07:36.180 --> 00:07:39.090
I could see the barbed wire
fence and the sentry tower

00:07:39.090 --> 00:07:41.870
right outside my
schoolhouse window

00:07:41.870 --> 00:07:49.210
as I recited the words with
liberty and justice for all.

00:07:49.210 --> 00:07:50.520
JULIE JAMES: Incredible.

00:07:50.520 --> 00:07:53.130
It's such an incredible
thing that you're

00:07:53.130 --> 00:07:56.120
going to be telling
this true life

00:07:56.120 --> 00:08:00.120
story, a mostly unknown
story of America,

00:08:00.120 --> 00:08:02.150
and events that
you lived through,

00:08:02.150 --> 00:08:04.300
but that you're going
to be reenacting

00:08:04.300 --> 00:08:06.190
these events on
a Broadway stage.

00:08:06.190 --> 00:08:09.140
What does that mean to you?

00:08:09.140 --> 00:08:11.450
GEORGE TAKEI: It's a very
meaningful experience for me,

00:08:11.450 --> 00:08:16.310
very exciting for me,
but it is profoundly

00:08:16.310 --> 00:08:19.740
meaningful to Japanese
American families

00:08:19.740 --> 00:08:23.830
and to the Japanese
American community.

00:08:23.830 --> 00:08:33.900
And like all musicals there is
the story of forbidden love.

00:08:33.900 --> 00:08:41.320
And it's an epic story of
the World War II battles.

00:08:41.320 --> 00:08:47.430
We tell the story of a heroic,
most decorated military unit

00:08:47.430 --> 00:08:50.370
in the entire Second
World War, which

00:08:50.370 --> 00:08:54.850
happened to be made up of
all Japanese Americans,

00:08:54.850 --> 00:08:57.320
the 442nd Regimental
Combat Team.

00:08:59.900 --> 00:09:06.200
But most of all, it's
a story of two people.

00:09:06.200 --> 00:09:13.860
A brother, I play Sammy,
and Sammy's sister,

00:09:13.860 --> 00:09:21.880
played by Lea Salonga, and it's
their story, their adventures.

00:09:21.880 --> 00:09:26.460
It's a story that
you've never heard,

00:09:26.460 --> 00:09:30.902
but a family that you
will never forget.

00:09:30.902 --> 00:09:31.860
JULIE JAMES: Beautiful.

00:09:31.860 --> 00:09:33.410
Beautifully said.

00:09:33.410 --> 00:09:39.810
So you know words
are powerful, and we

00:09:39.810 --> 00:09:44.450
have a lot of great
plays on Broadway.

00:09:44.450 --> 00:09:46.690
Why did you think
that a musical would

00:09:46.690 --> 00:09:49.410
be the best way
to tell the story

00:09:49.410 --> 00:09:53.170
of "Allegiance"
and your history?

00:09:53.170 --> 00:09:58.720
GEORGE TAKEI: Words have the
power of reaching the brain,

00:09:58.720 --> 00:10:00.630
set us thinking.

00:10:00.630 --> 00:10:05.150
Music reaches the
heart, our feelings,

00:10:05.150 --> 00:10:08.200
and when you combine the
two together in a musical

00:10:08.200 --> 00:10:11.580
it becomes a singular force.

00:10:11.580 --> 00:10:15.300
It is a beautiful
story that we tell,

00:10:15.300 --> 00:10:22.590
and that story is still too
little known in this country.

00:10:22.590 --> 00:10:26.360
And so I've spent most of my
adult life talking about it

00:10:26.360 --> 00:10:33.540
to universities, to
governmental agencies,

00:10:33.540 --> 00:10:35.870
and to corporate groups.

00:10:35.870 --> 00:10:38.870
And we've developed
a musical about it,

00:10:38.870 --> 00:10:42.570
and this is what's
so exciting to me.

00:10:42.570 --> 00:10:47.760
And I consider this
musical my legacy project,

00:10:47.760 --> 00:10:53.450
and my husband, Brad,
shares with me this passion

00:10:53.450 --> 00:10:56.330
to get our legacy
project on Broadway.

00:10:56.330 --> 00:10:57.720
JULIE JAMES: Oh,
that's so sweet.

00:10:57.720 --> 00:10:59.090
Is Brad here?

00:10:59.090 --> 00:11:00.560
Hi, Brad.

00:11:00.560 --> 00:11:02.545
Everybody, Brad Takei.

00:11:06.750 --> 00:11:10.530
It's so great to see
you here and the fact

00:11:10.530 --> 00:11:15.210
that he's by your side
and believing in you 100%

00:11:15.210 --> 00:11:18.270
and helping shepherd
this is fantastic.

00:11:18.270 --> 00:11:20.910
It's so great to see you, Brad.

00:11:20.910 --> 00:11:24.130
So now, in the show
"Allegiance," you play,

00:11:24.130 --> 00:11:27.020
not one, but two
characters, right?

00:11:27.020 --> 00:11:28.680
GEORGE TAKEI: That's correct.

00:11:28.680 --> 00:11:32.440
In the San Diego production
at the Old Globe,

00:11:32.440 --> 00:11:37.650
I had the pleasure of the
sharing the role of Sam Kimura

00:11:37.650 --> 00:11:41.727
with a very talented
young man, Telly Leung.

00:11:41.727 --> 00:11:42.810
JULIE JAMES: I love Telly.

00:11:42.810 --> 00:11:45.740
GEORGE TAKEI: Oh, yeah,
he's a fantastic performer.

00:11:45.740 --> 00:11:51.610
And Telly plays
Sam as a young man

00:11:51.610 --> 00:11:53.510
during the period
of the internment.

00:11:53.510 --> 00:11:59.720
And I play Sam in the
present, many years later.

00:11:59.720 --> 00:12:06.470
But I also play Sam's
grandfather, an immigrant man

00:12:06.470 --> 00:12:11.320
who came to this country
with hope and ambition.

00:12:11.320 --> 00:12:15.640
And he's something of a rascal.

00:12:15.640 --> 00:12:16.640
JULIE JAMES: Typcasting?

00:12:20.370 --> 00:12:22.700
Typecasting, I hear?

00:12:22.700 --> 00:12:26.550
Telly is, of course, a
veteran of the Broadway stage.

00:12:26.550 --> 00:12:30.060
You might have seen him
in "Wicked," or "Rent,"

00:12:30.060 --> 00:12:32.110
or "Godspell."

00:12:32.110 --> 00:12:35.250
Many fans will recognize
him from "Glee,"

00:12:35.250 --> 00:12:39.920
