00:23:43.840 --> 00:23:45.260
What does that mean?

00:23:45.260 --> 00:23:48.250
That's a citizen
defined in the negative.

00:23:48.250 --> 00:23:51.060
They even took the word
citizen away from us

00:23:51.060 --> 00:23:53.800
and put us in
these prison camps.

00:23:53.800 --> 00:23:55.820
How do we tap them?

00:23:55.820 --> 00:24:01.210
Their solution was a
outrageous solution, a loyalty

00:24:01.210 --> 00:24:04.350
questionnaire, which was
a series of questions.

00:24:04.350 --> 00:24:08.590
But there are two key questions
that everyone in the camp

00:24:08.590 --> 00:24:10.190
had to respond to.

00:24:10.190 --> 00:24:19.310
Everyone over 17 years of age,
from 17 to 87, man or woman,

00:24:19.310 --> 00:24:23.540
American born or an immigrant.

00:24:23.540 --> 00:24:27.110
Question 27, one of the two
controversial questions,

00:24:27.110 --> 00:24:30.040
asked will you
bear arms to defend

00:24:30.040 --> 00:24:31.760
the United States of America?

00:24:31.760 --> 00:24:34.960
This being asked of a
17-year-old young man

00:24:34.960 --> 00:24:39.450
or an 87-year-old
immigrant lady.

00:24:39.450 --> 00:24:41.620
It was preposterous.

00:24:41.620 --> 00:24:45.160
Question 28 was one
sentence, and it

00:24:45.160 --> 00:24:50.910
was a very insidious sentence
with two opposite ideas.

00:24:50.910 --> 00:24:54.360
It asked will you swear
your loyalty to the United

00:24:54.360 --> 00:24:59.180
States of America and
forswear your loyalty

00:24:59.180 --> 00:25:01.780
to the emperor of Japan?

00:25:01.780 --> 00:25:03.690
We're Americans.

00:25:03.690 --> 00:25:08.190
For the government to assume
that we're born with a loyalty

00:25:08.190 --> 00:25:11.390
to the emperor, that
there's something genetic

00:25:11.390 --> 00:25:15.190
about a loyalty to the
emperor, was outrageous.

00:25:15.190 --> 00:25:18.620
You can't forswear something
that you don't have.

00:25:18.620 --> 00:25:25.310
So my father said, they took my
business, they took our home,

00:25:25.310 --> 00:25:27.570
they took our
freedom, the one thing

00:25:27.570 --> 00:25:30.220
I'm not going to give
them is my dignity.

00:25:30.220 --> 00:25:32.920
I am not going to grovel
before this government.

00:25:32.920 --> 00:25:37.870
He answered no, and for that
he was labeled disloyal.

00:25:37.870 --> 00:25:42.030
There was another group
of young men who said,

00:25:42.030 --> 00:25:45.290
I will fight for my country
because I'm an American,

00:25:45.290 --> 00:25:49.220
but I will fight as an American.

00:25:49.220 --> 00:25:54.150
If I can report to my hometown
draft board with my family

00:25:54.150 --> 00:25:57.310
back home, I will
fight for this country,

00:25:57.310 --> 00:26:01.440
but I will not go
as an internee going

00:26:01.440 --> 00:26:04.610
from behind these barbed wire
fences, leaving my family

00:26:04.610 --> 00:26:06.430
and loved ones behind.

00:26:06.430 --> 00:26:10.680
And for that courageous,
principled stand

00:26:10.680 --> 00:26:15.570
they were tried for draft
evasion, found guilty,

00:26:15.570 --> 00:26:19.420
and thrown into
federal penitentiaries.

00:26:19.420 --> 00:26:23.280
But there's another
amazing group of people.

00:26:23.280 --> 00:26:28.910
These young men bit the
bullet, and women too, they

00:26:28.910 --> 00:26:32.560
bit the bullet,
swallowed their pride

00:26:32.560 --> 00:26:37.640
and answered both questions as
the government wanted them to,

00:26:37.640 --> 00:26:41.320
and they went from behind
these barbed wire fences,

00:26:41.320 --> 00:26:44.470
putting on the same uniform
as that of the sentries that

00:26:44.470 --> 00:26:47.480
guarded over us,
leaving their family

00:26:47.480 --> 00:26:53.290
and loved ones in imprisonment
to fight for this country.

00:26:53.290 --> 00:26:56.870
And their story is
an amazing story.

00:26:56.870 --> 00:27:02.930
They fought with incredible
courage and valor.

00:27:02.930 --> 00:27:05.370
They sustained the
highest combat casualty

00:27:05.370 --> 00:27:10.020
rate of any unit of
it's comparable size,

00:27:10.020 --> 00:27:14.760
and they came back the
single most decorated unit

00:27:14.760 --> 00:27:16.490
of the entire war.

00:27:16.490 --> 00:27:19.540
They were welcomed back
to the United States

00:27:19.540 --> 00:27:22.600
on the White House lawn
by President Truman, who

00:27:22.600 --> 00:27:28.010
said to them, you fought not
only the enemy, but prejudice,

00:27:28.010 --> 00:27:28.920
and you won.

00:27:31.770 --> 00:27:33.470
JULIE JAMES: That's incredible.

00:27:33.470 --> 00:27:36.150
You know, I think one of the
things that really strikes me

00:27:36.150 --> 00:27:41.240
about this story, your
story, is that throughout all

00:27:41.240 --> 00:27:44.030
of this, at the
same time, you're

00:27:44.030 --> 00:27:47.470
keeping up some
sense of normalcy.

00:27:47.470 --> 00:27:49.580
It's just absolutely incredible.

00:27:49.580 --> 00:27:51.240
Tell us a little bit about that.

00:27:51.240 --> 00:27:52.560
GEORGE TAKEI: Well, it's
my parents actually.

00:27:52.560 --> 00:27:52.870
JULIE JAMES: Yeah?

00:27:52.870 --> 00:27:54.745
GEORGE TAKEI: And all
the adults that did it.

00:27:54.745 --> 00:27:59.350
Yes, we tried to have normalcy
while living in those black tar

00:27:59.350 --> 00:28:01.010
paper barracks.

00:28:01.010 --> 00:28:04.260
My mother's scavenged
around and got

00:28:04.260 --> 00:28:08.870
the military to give her
some scrap military fabric,

00:28:08.870 --> 00:28:13.440
and she made curtains
for our barrack windows

00:28:13.440 --> 00:28:16.140
so that we'd have some privacy.

00:28:16.140 --> 00:28:18.140
There are some who
had green thumbs,

00:28:18.140 --> 00:28:20.660
and they took that
barren landscape

00:28:20.660 --> 00:28:25.280
and turned it into bountiful,
productive victory gardens,

00:28:25.280 --> 00:28:27.020
if you will.

00:28:27.020 --> 00:28:31.060
And there are others who
were handy with crafts,

00:28:31.060 --> 00:28:33.450
and they worked on crafts.

00:28:33.450 --> 00:28:36.090
My father loved
baseball and he was

00:28:36.090 --> 00:28:39.940
a member of our
block baseball team.

00:28:39.940 --> 00:28:46.430
And I remember going to
sleep at the end of the day,

00:28:46.430 --> 00:28:49.970
my mother put us to bed
early because we were kids,

00:28:49.970 --> 00:28:56.500
hearing the songs of the
1940s, because the camp command

00:28:56.500 --> 00:29:01.290
occasionally, about every other
month, allowed the young people

00:29:01.290 --> 00:29:05.410
to have dances in the
mess hall after dinner.

00:29:05.410 --> 00:29:08.270
They cleared the tables
and the benches away

00:29:08.270 --> 00:29:11.370
and played their
dance songs, or they

00:29:11.370 --> 00:29:13.560
may have performed themselves.

00:29:13.560 --> 00:29:17.000
And I went to bed
listening to the big band

00:29:17.000 --> 00:29:21.800
sound of Tommy Dorsey, or The
Andrews Sisters, the swing

00:29:21.800 --> 00:29:24.320
sound, or the bebop sounds.

00:29:24.320 --> 00:29:27.090
And so that's one
of the fond memories

00:29:27.090 --> 00:29:33.060
of my childhood
in a prison camp.

00:29:33.060 --> 00:29:34.180
JULIE JAMES: Yeah.

