00:50:38.229 --> 00:50:39.020
AUDIENCE: Hi there.

00:50:39.020 --> 00:50:41.220
I want to thank you
guys for coming.

00:50:41.220 --> 00:50:43.230
I love to ask Broadway
performers when

00:50:43.230 --> 00:50:45.300
they come a bit about
their experience,

00:50:45.300 --> 00:50:47.860
putting their own personality
into the show and ad libbing,

00:50:47.860 --> 00:50:49.484
but I think it's a
great opportunity we

00:50:49.484 --> 00:50:51.326
have some of the
behind the scenes group

00:50:51.326 --> 00:50:52.450
here that makes it happens.

00:50:52.450 --> 00:50:55.130
So I'd love to hear
from your perspective ad

00:50:55.130 --> 00:50:57.610
libbing, adapting the
show after it's written,

00:50:57.610 --> 00:51:00.160
is that something you
encourage, you have a part in?

00:51:00.160 --> 00:51:01.930
Is that solely up to the actors?

00:51:01.930 --> 00:51:04.020
I'd love to hear
your take on that.

00:51:04.020 --> 00:51:08.380
STAFFORD ARIMA: Oh I think that
once a show has been written

00:51:08.380 --> 00:51:10.580
and we have a group
of authors who

00:51:10.580 --> 00:51:17.000
have created dialogue and
lyrics and specific words

00:51:17.000 --> 00:51:21.630
to say that the hope
is that the actor will

00:51:21.630 --> 00:51:24.280
remain kind of on book.

00:51:24.280 --> 00:51:28.700
Meaning, will say the words
that have been written as is.

00:51:28.700 --> 00:51:34.050
I think that the element of
something feeling spontaneous

00:51:34.050 --> 00:51:37.720
on stage, which is why a
lot of audience members

00:51:37.720 --> 00:51:40.910
enjoy the live theater
performances because it does

00:51:40.910 --> 00:51:47.960
feel alive and spontaneous, that
comes from an actor's bringing

00:51:47.960 --> 00:51:52.870
to the material a kind of
reality of that moment.

00:51:52.870 --> 00:51:55.270
If a performer
perhaps kind of zones

00:51:55.270 --> 00:51:59.150
into just kind of
like doing it by rote,

00:51:59.150 --> 00:52:01.990
then the performance
might feel stale.

00:52:01.990 --> 00:52:06.760
But you know 99% of performers,
when they're in a show stay

00:52:06.760 --> 00:52:09.820
kind of alive with the
material, but still

00:52:09.820 --> 00:52:12.750
have the kind of context
of this is the words

00:52:12.750 --> 00:52:15.570
that I have to say, this is
the blocking that I have to do.

00:52:15.570 --> 00:52:19.430
Because in theater, you
know, lights are created,

00:52:19.430 --> 00:52:22.120
spotlights are created,
there are specific areas

00:52:22.120 --> 00:52:24.980
of the stage that the
actor needs to go to.

00:52:24.980 --> 00:52:26.870
So if the actor decided
one day, oh, I just

00:52:26.870 --> 00:52:32.160
want to walk around the stage
and not follow what was given,

00:52:32.160 --> 00:52:34.654
then he or she might be
out of the light and all

00:52:34.654 --> 00:52:35.570
of that kind of stuff.

00:52:35.570 --> 00:52:38.490
So I think, in
essence, spontaneity

00:52:38.490 --> 00:52:43.730
and an honest performance
will come from an aliveness,

00:52:43.730 --> 00:52:46.445
but still within the
context of the material.

00:52:46.445 --> 00:52:48.320
MARC ACITO: The performers
make it their own.

00:52:48.320 --> 00:52:50.340
I think that's what
the audience senses

00:52:50.340 --> 00:52:51.920
when it feels spontaneous.

00:52:51.920 --> 00:52:53.990
We watched Melinda
Doolittle today,

00:52:53.990 --> 00:52:57.169
and that's the first time
I've heard her sing that song.

00:52:57.169 --> 00:52:59.210
And, you know, hearing it
in context of the show,

00:52:59.210 --> 00:53:01.630
it feels like it's one thing,
and it's part of this story

00:53:01.630 --> 00:53:03.130
that we've already
been telling you,

00:53:03.130 --> 00:53:05.140
but what it pointed
out to me was just

00:53:05.140 --> 00:53:07.900
how universal that story is.

00:53:07.900 --> 00:53:10.120
How it felt like it was
Melinda Doolittle's story.

00:53:10.120 --> 00:53:12.180
I'm thinking about, oh,
I didn't know she had,

00:53:12.180 --> 00:53:15.660
you know, a swing when she
was a kid, Melinda Doolittle.

00:53:15.660 --> 00:53:20.660
And we wrote it, but it felt--
they make it so their own,

00:53:20.660 --> 00:53:24.200
you feel as if it's
them speaking to you.

00:53:24.200 --> 00:53:28.160
And with Melinda, I'd follow
her anywhere, you know.

