00:53:44.660 --> 00:53:47.380
But what's your question
here in the audience today?

00:53:47.380 --> 00:53:49.010
AUDIENCE: Hi, this
is for George.

00:53:49.010 --> 00:53:51.540
I was curious how
much you had to do

00:53:51.540 --> 00:53:54.560
with the writing versus
just providing the story.

00:53:54.560 --> 00:53:56.760
Like did you provide dialogue?

00:53:56.760 --> 00:53:57.950
GEORGE TAKEI: No.

00:53:57.950 --> 00:54:01.810
We have some gifted
writers here.

00:54:01.810 --> 00:54:06.800
It actually began in
a Broadway theater.

00:54:06.800 --> 00:54:10.662
Brad and I went to
see-- well, actually it

00:54:10.662 --> 00:54:15.640
began in an off Broadway
theater, forbidden Broadway.

00:54:15.640 --> 00:54:19.860
And there were two guys
seated in front of us.

00:54:19.860 --> 00:54:23.240
They happen to be
Lorenzo and Jay, who

00:54:23.240 --> 00:54:26.560
I didn't know from Adam, but
they recognized my voice,

00:54:26.560 --> 00:54:32.100
and they turned around and
we chatted a little bit.

00:54:32.100 --> 00:54:35.220
I guess I have a
recognizable voice.

00:54:35.220 --> 00:54:37.310
And we saw that they
were theater lovers.

00:54:37.310 --> 00:54:40.640
And that evening Brad and I went
back to our apartment saying,

00:54:40.640 --> 00:54:44.100
yeah, it's wonderful to have
chatted with those guys.

00:54:44.100 --> 00:54:48.750
The next night we went
to see "In the Heights,"

00:54:48.750 --> 00:54:52.910
the Puerto Rican family
in Washington Heights,

00:54:52.910 --> 00:54:56.080
and we walked into
the theater and there

00:54:56.080 --> 00:54:58.800
were those two same guys
seated in the theater.

00:54:58.800 --> 00:55:02.150
JAY KUO: They thought that
we were stalking them.

00:55:02.150 --> 00:55:06.430
GEORGE TAKEI: And our
seats were in the same row.

00:55:06.430 --> 00:55:10.160
We did think you
were stalking us.

00:55:10.160 --> 00:55:12.650
JAY KUO: At some
point during Act One,

00:55:12.650 --> 00:55:15.860
there's a song called
"Inutil," which means useless.

00:55:15.860 --> 00:55:17.010
GEORGE TAKEI: Inutil.

00:55:17.010 --> 00:55:21.010
Your Spanish
pronunciation is terrible.

00:55:21.010 --> 00:55:23.590
JAY KUO: And I
looked over and I saw

00:55:23.590 --> 00:55:26.740
George crying during that song,
so during the intermission

00:55:26.740 --> 00:55:30.170
I asked him what had moved
him so much during that song,

00:55:30.170 --> 00:55:34.429
and he started telling me about
how the notion of uselessness

00:55:34.429 --> 00:55:36.470
really resonated with him
because his father felt

00:55:36.470 --> 00:55:39.204
so useless trying to
protect and preserve

00:55:39.204 --> 00:55:41.120
their family while they
were in the internment

00:55:41.120 --> 00:55:42.110
camps of Arkansas.

00:55:42.110 --> 00:55:45.220
And every hair on
my body stood on end

00:55:45.220 --> 00:55:48.050
because I was hearing for
the first time this story

00:55:48.050 --> 00:55:50.140
and realizing this
is a terrific story.

00:55:50.140 --> 00:55:52.154
And I just turned
to Lorenzo and I

00:55:52.154 --> 00:55:53.820
said are you thinking
what I'm thinking.

00:55:53.820 --> 00:55:54.815
And we said--

00:55:54.815 --> 00:55:57.190
LORENZO THIONE: It's like a
quintessential American epic.

00:55:57.190 --> 00:55:59.610
Just the type of struggle
that these people had

00:55:59.610 --> 00:56:02.530
to endure for a country that
many had come and sought

00:56:02.530 --> 00:56:05.840
after as a promised
land, was just

00:56:05.840 --> 00:56:07.950
something that we
thought was a story that

00:56:07.950 --> 00:56:09.731
would resonate with
audiences everywhere.

00:56:09.731 --> 00:56:11.480
JAY KUO: And so just
a few weeks later, we

00:56:11.480 --> 00:56:17.830
had sent sort of a review of it.

00:56:17.830 --> 00:56:19.626
LORENZO THIONE: Jay works fast.

00:56:19.626 --> 00:56:21.250
GEORGE TAKEI: Yeah,
a few weeks later I

00:56:21.250 --> 00:56:26.260
got a song on my computer,
and I listened to it,

00:56:26.260 --> 00:56:29.480
and I was bawling at
my computer again.

00:56:29.480 --> 00:56:32.500
And so I invited them to come to
the Japanese American National

00:56:32.500 --> 00:56:35.880
Museum, which we
founded in Los Angeles.

00:56:35.880 --> 00:56:38.040
It's an affiliate
of the Smithsonian,

00:56:38.040 --> 00:56:42.350
and introduced them to the
details of the internment

00:56:42.350 --> 00:56:43.832
experience.

00:56:43.832 --> 00:56:45.290
JULIE JAMES: That's
so fascinating.

00:56:45.290 --> 00:56:46.915
MARC ACITO: On top
of that, though, I'd

00:56:46.915 --> 00:56:49.030
like to add that the
story, of course,

00:56:49.030 --> 00:56:51.244
is inspired by
George's true story,

00:56:51.244 --> 00:56:52.660
and the creation
of the characters

00:56:52.660 --> 00:56:54.730
were really inspired
by him as well.

00:56:54.730 --> 00:56:56.410
When I came on to
the project George

00:56:56.410 --> 00:57:00.000
was playing Sam, which
is a very serious part,

00:57:00.000 --> 00:57:03.020
and there's the chance for
him to play some high drama,

00:57:03.020 --> 00:57:05.660
but there wasn't any place
for him to play comedy.

00:57:05.660 --> 00:57:09.390
And I said, this
sci-fi legend has now

00:57:09.390 --> 00:57:11.580
become an internet
comedy legend and I said,

00:57:11.580 --> 00:57:14.130
you've got to give this
guy something to do.

00:57:14.130 --> 00:57:16.040
So we invented the
role of Ojii-San

00:57:16.040 --> 00:57:18.560
for him to be able to
have that other side.

00:57:18.560 --> 00:57:20.690
And it really speaks to
what inspired me most

00:57:20.690 --> 00:57:23.620
about the story,
is the absolute--

00:57:23.620 --> 00:57:28.140
the intrepid quality that the
Japanese American people had

00:57:28.140 --> 00:57:30.420
and the way they kept
their sense of humor

00:57:30.420 --> 00:57:32.031
and the way in
which they blossomed

00:57:32.031 --> 00:57:33.030
where they were planted.

00:57:33.030 --> 00:57:37.630
They grew so much
in their gardens

00:57:37.630 --> 00:57:40.770
that they actually had a surplus
that they supplied the war

00:57:40.770 --> 00:57:43.820
department in a place
that nobody ever

00:57:43.820 --> 00:57:44.990
thought anything would grow.

00:57:44.990 --> 00:57:47.060
They bloomed where
they were planted.

00:57:47.060 --> 00:57:49.670
It's a daily inspiration to us.

00:57:49.670 --> 00:57:53.070
I mean, truly you
have to own gaman.

00:57:53.070 --> 00:57:54.820
If the subway goes
away, and you're like,

00:57:54.820 --> 00:57:55.944
oh, I have a terrible life.

00:57:55.944 --> 00:57:58.630
You're like no one's putting
me in a camp, gaman, you know?

00:58:02.780 --> 00:58:04.410
JULIE JAMES: Perfectly said.

00:58:04.410 --> 00:58:07.575
We have a great question
from The G-dog in Fremont.

00:58:10.240 --> 00:58:12.250
Got to love that screen name.

00:58:12.250 --> 00:58:16.510
Having seen the
show in San Diego,

00:58:16.510 --> 00:58:18.430
I'm curious what
changes are being

00:58:18.430 --> 00:58:20.730
made for the eventual
Broadway version?

00:58:20.730 --> 00:58:22.258
Good question.

00:58:22.258 --> 00:58:23.530
MARC ACITO: A lot.

00:58:23.530 --> 00:58:25.946
STAFFORD ARIMA: Do you
want to speak to that?

00:58:25.946 --> 00:58:31.530
MARC ACITO: I think it
has become more refined.

00:58:31.530 --> 00:58:36.270
The show runs the gamut
in terms of its bandwidth

00:58:36.270 --> 00:58:38.960
of it's-- it'd be so easy
for this to be considered

00:58:38.960 --> 00:58:39.620
a tragedy.

00:58:39.620 --> 00:58:42.870
But at the same time, it's the
triumph of the human spirit.

00:58:42.870 --> 00:58:45.710
So finding that full
range and the balance

00:58:45.710 --> 00:58:47.410
between those
things where we can

00:58:47.410 --> 00:58:51.134
take the audience to despair
and then uplift them has been,

00:58:51.134 --> 00:58:52.050
I think, a real focus.

00:58:52.050 --> 00:58:53.890
JAY KUO: We've worked
on a lot of new music.

00:58:53.890 --> 00:58:57.430
And Lynne-- it's a real
pleasure to work with Lynne,

00:58:57.430 --> 00:58:59.770
arranging some of the
new songs and working

00:58:59.770 --> 00:59:02.315
that up together, especially
for this presentation.

00:59:02.315 --> 00:59:04.750
LYNNE SHANKEL: Yes.

00:59:04.750 --> 00:59:08.290
What the two ladies sang
today, "Stronger than Before,"

00:59:08.290 --> 00:59:11.890
was an arrangement that I made
specifically for this event.

00:59:11.890 --> 00:59:16.690
Like it's a lot poppier than
it is in the show itself,

00:59:16.690 --> 00:59:19.190
and we just kind
of wanted to show

00:59:19.190 --> 00:59:20.420
a different side of things.

00:59:20.420 --> 00:59:22.140
Along with what Jay
was saying, just

00:59:22.140 --> 00:59:25.630
to really show that these
themes really are universal.

00:59:25.630 --> 00:59:30.930
That it's not just a show
about Asians for Asians.

00:59:30.930 --> 00:59:32.830
That these themes are universal.

00:59:32.830 --> 00:59:37.380
I mean, I can relate
to all of the songs

00:59:37.380 --> 00:59:39.740
that we've sung today.

00:59:39.740 --> 00:59:42.950
But we have a lot of
exciting new material.

00:59:42.950 --> 00:59:45.040
Been working on a new
opening number, the number

00:59:45.040 --> 00:59:47.690
that you heard today,
and a couple more,

00:59:47.690 --> 00:59:49.566
and I'm so excited to
get back to work on it.

00:59:49.566 --> 00:59:51.898
LORENZO THIONE: I just want
to add just one thing, which

00:59:51.898 --> 00:59:54.890
is even San Diego came sort of
midway through a development

00:59:54.890 --> 00:59:59.060
process that had taken years,
and the process has continued.

00:59:59.060 --> 01:00:03.250
One thing that we've
been pleasantly

01:00:03.250 --> 01:00:06.460
surprised at the
fact that no matter

01:00:06.460 --> 01:00:08.220
how much the show had
changed, no matter

01:00:08.220 --> 01:00:11.210
how many new scenes, no matter
how many new numbers, no matter

01:00:11.210 --> 01:00:14.070
how many songs we would cut,
and there are more songs

01:00:14.070 --> 01:00:18.290
cut than there are in the
show, and then put back,

01:00:18.290 --> 01:00:20.960
it always felt
like the same show.

01:00:20.960 --> 01:00:23.420
It always felt like the
story we we're telling

01:00:23.420 --> 01:00:26.940
and the journey we were
bringing the audience with us on

01:00:26.940 --> 01:00:27.940
was the same one.

01:00:27.940 --> 01:00:30.130
And that sort of
reinforced in us

01:00:30.130 --> 01:00:31.910
the idea that we
were making progress

01:00:31.910 --> 01:00:34.579
towards the right goal.

01:00:34.579 --> 01:00:35.620
JULIE JAMES: Really good.

